`LINE_STRIPE` is not the proper [Primitive](https://www.khronos.org/opengl/wiki/Primitive#Line_primitives) type to do what you want, because a line strip is one coherently line.  
Use the primitive type `LINES`. So each branch creates a separated line segment:

The function has to calculate the end point of the current branch and to add the 2 vertices for the line segment to the point list:

```lang-js
let x2 = x + length * Math.sin(angle);
let y2 = y + length * Math.cos(angle);

points.push(x, y, x2, y2);
```

And 2 new branches at the end of the current branch by e recursive call:

```lang-js
createPoints(depth-1, x2, y2, length/2, angle+Math.PI/4, points);
createPoints(depth-1, x2, y2, length/2, angle-Math.PI/4, points);
```

Complete coding of the function:

```lang-js
function createPoints(depth, x, y, length, angle, points) {

    if (depth &lt;= 0)
        return;

    // end of current line segment
    let x2 = x + length * Math.sin(angle);
    let y2 = y + length * Math.cos(angle);

    // add segment
    points.push(x, y, x2, y2);

    // create 2 branches
    createPoints(depth-1, x2, y2, length/2, angle+Math.PI/4, points);
    createPoints(depth-1, x2, y2, length/2, angle-Math.PI/4, points);
}
```

e.g. 4 levels:

```lang-js
let points = [];
createPoints(4, 0, -1.0, 1.0, 0.0, points);
```

[![][1]][1]


---

If you anyway want to use the primitive type `LINE_STRIP`, then each branch has to add a single end point, but has to return to this point after each child branch:

```
function createPointsStrip(depth, x, y, length, angle, points) {

    if (depth &lt;= 0)
        return;

    // end of current line segment
    let x2 = x + length * Math.sin(angle);
    let y2 = y + length * Math.cos(angle);

    // add point
    points.push(x2, y2);

    // create 2 branches
    createPointsStrip(depth-1, x2, y2, length/2, angle+Math.PI/4, points);
    points.push(x2, y2);
    createPointsStrip(depth-1, x2, y2, length/2, angle-Math.PI/4, points);
    points.push(x2, y2);
}
```

The first point has to be add to the list of points, before the recursive function is called:

```lang-js
let points = [0.0, -1.0];
createPointsStrip(4, 0, -1.0, 1.0, 0.0, points);
```

The generated primitive is completely different, but looks the same (in this case). 


